\begin_layout Subsection
Depreciation Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Companies need to decide, which method (or their combination) to use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to choosing the method, an assumption is to be made about the
 residual (salvage) value of the asset - the amount it can be sold for at
 the end of its useful life.
 The depreciable value is the difference between the acquisition cost and
 the estimated residual value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important that all depreciation techniques must yield the same residual
 value at the end (otherwise the value would depend on the method, which
 is impossible).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most popular methods are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Straight-line depreciation - spread the depreciable value equally over the
 useful life.
 This method is very simple, unbiased, doesn't require assumptions and provides
 forecast of the depreciation.
 The disadvantage is missing the matching between the revenues and expenses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Depreciation based on activity/units - better match the depreciation expense
 to the revenues.
 A depreciation rate per unit is determined, then multipled by actual usage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Accelerated depreciation - writing off costs quicker than the straight-line
 method.
 Double-declining balance is its most popular way (doubling the straight-line
 method, then multiplying by the beginning book value).
\end_layout

